		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2008 SI"></a><br><code>sle2008s/paper02</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2008 SI</a> paper:</span><br><i>The “Physics” of Notations: Toward a Scientific Basis for Constructing Visual Notations in Software Engineering</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/DanielLaurenceMoody.html">Daniel Laurence Moody</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1109/TSE.2009.67">10.1109/TSE.2009.67</a></li>
<li>Extended version of <a href="../sle2008/paper01.html"><em>Evaluating the Visual Syntax of UML: An Analysis of the Cognitive Effectiveness of the UML Family of Diagrams</em></a> (SLE 2008)</li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagM">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> The paper develops a principled design theory (principles and rationale) for constructing visual modelling notations, i.e., language design for visual syntax.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL">T5H: Usability</span></a><ul><li> The proposed principles aim at cognitively effective notations and improved human comprehensibility, making usability a central evaluation dimension.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4f.html"><span class="tagL">T4F: Visualisation</span></a><ul><li> It focuses on the visual (diagrammatic) representation of language constructs and how they should be visualised for effective communication.
</li></ul></li></ul>
